status_message:
From our sports writer Paul Klauda on Sid's return:

On a day when snow snarled the commute and many Minnesotans heeded advice to stay off the roads, almost 97-year-old Sid -- barely three weeks after breaking his hip in a fall -- roared back into the office. 

With a walker. And a personal care provider. And a column to write for Thursday. 

"You have 18,000 bylines in the Star Tribune and we think you need a few more," the sports editor told him before a gathering of sports staffers outside his office. "We're all glad to have you back." 

Somewhat at a loss for how to mark the occasion, we got him balloons and a cake. There's no script for a comeback like this. Breaking a hip at Sid's age can often start a spiral of other maladies. 

Not so with Sid. Heck, last Friday he got himself to the press conference to announce new Gophers football coach P.J. Fleck. Seated in the front row, he got up afterward and greeted Fleck, as he has every Gopher coach for the last 70 years. 

His caregiver was with him then, too. She's no slouch. After Sid supposedly ragged on her driving (probably, one editor said, for obeying red lights), she pulled over and told Sidney in no uncertain terms that she's cared for people a lot more important than him. Not one of them, she said, had died because of her driving. 

Sid was quiet after that. Some sports department wags figured he was trying to figure out who could be a bigger deal than he was. 

"There's a couple rooms you can go in," he told her as he got into his office and seemed concerned about what she would do while he worked. "You got something to read or something?" 

Then Sid sat down with his assistant, he dictated his column, and all seemed normal again in the sports department. 

"I really appreciate it," Sid had said a few minutes earlier, after getting a round of applause from all of us. "All you guys have been great to me, and for an old man who can barely make it." 

"You will," someone called out. Sid: "We'll see what happens." 

Welcome back, Sid!
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
The Minnesota Twins announced plans to honor Jacob Wetterling at Friday's game by wearing red jerseys with a number 11 patch  — the visiting Cleveland Indians will also wear the #11forJacob patch. 

The Wetterling family asked to put on the number 11 and live by these 11 traits:

1. Be fair
2. Be kind
3. Be understanding
4. Be honest
5. Be thankful
6. Be a good sport
7. Be a good friend
8. Be joyful
9. Be generous
10. Be gentle with others
11. Be positive

status_message:
"Today after work I decided to see what our National Cemetery looked like in a snow storm. As I had envisioned, Fort Snelling National Cemetery was beautiful, row upon, perfect row of graves partially obscured by freshly falling snow. Never did I think someone would be out there. But almost out of nowhere a woman appeared walking over to a nearby grave. I took several photos of the scene before she almost as quickly disappeared. I now regret having not flagged her down and found out her story and the story of her loved one. Sometimes that is the dilemma of journalism—to disturb or to just observe. I'm glad I was fortunate enough to have witnessed this scene."

-- Star Tribune photographer David Joles

Please share to spread the word: Man flees downtown Minneapolis courtroom, is still on the loose after being found guilty of attempted murder.

Michael David Henderson escaped from the Hennepin County Government Center in Minneapolis today after being convicted of 2nd degree attempted murder.  

He was last seen wearing a maroon t-shirt, dark colored dress pants, and black dress shoes. He's described as being 5'5", 145 pounds, with short hair, a scruffy beard, wearing a solid maroon shirt, black pants and white shoes. A mugshot from his arrest after the Sam's Club robbery shows him with longer hair. 

Police say if you spot this man to call 911.

status_message:
Many of you were moved by the story of Jason, who has brain cancer and has been tending the memorial of slain Mendota Heights police officer Scott Patrick. Our Paul Klauda has this update:

Jason is now providing light to others.

When I met him last week, he was tending to candles at the memorial site where Mendota Heights police officer Scott Patrick was killed. I went back Thursday evening, mostly to convey the magnitude of reaction to a post I did after that visit.

Hundreds of thousands of people saw his story after the Star Tribune, my employer, reposted the picture on its Facebook page. Thousands of "likes" and more than 180 comments were left, all of them lauding Jason's simple act of tending to the memorial. 

It was Patrick who had spent 30 minutes talking with Jason last December after giving him a speeding ticket. Jason said he had just left the hospital after learning some bad news related to his cancer.

As the days have taken their toll on the memorial's flowers and candles, Jason's daily visits have turned him into a gardener -- weeding out dead flowers, caring for new ones, seeing to small flags rimming the boulevard site. He leaves the candles, or what's left of them, to evening visitors to light in the darkness.

The light provided by Jason comes when one woman stops by and, after asking "Are you Jason?" tells him he's "the guardian angel" of the community.  It comes when one of officer Patrick's family members walks up, shakes his hand and spends several minutes talking like neighbors.

And it comes when this woman introduces herself and her son, who also has a brain tumor. They trade details, hopes and tears for several minutes.

"You are an inspiration," she tells Jason over and over.

Jason looks at her son, a big teenager who works at a fast-food outlet, smiles and calls him the inspiration.

"It's not about me," Jason told me more than once since last week.

"I just want to build community," he said, "with whatever time I have left."
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
His name is Jason. He spends three to four hours every day, lighting and re-lighting candles at the makeshift roadside memorial where Mendota Heights police officer Scott Patrick was killed last week. 

Our Paul Klauda asked him why. 

His story: Officer Patrick stopped him for speeding last December as Jason, who has brain cancer, left the hospital. He got a ticket, but also a 30-minute conversation that, in the wake of the officer's death, made him value the preciousness of life just a little bit more. 

Jason plans to be there on Wednesday, tending to the candles when the massive  funeral procession bearing Patrick's flag-draped casket rolls by, escorted by hundreds of police cars. 

Jason said doctors told him he wouldn't live this long. He says he thankful for the chance to help others with whatever time he has left. 

Photo by Paul Klauda, Star Tribune

(Edit: Paul wanted to add that when he talked to Jason he was there more for personal reasons than as a journalist, having stopped by the memorial after attending the visitation and spending time with Scott Patrick's brother, who is a longtime friend.)

Dean Barkley says the ordeal started in April. He had lent the vehicle to a relative to haul some tires. That relative was driving the SUV when he got pulled over on Interstate 394, and Golden Valley police charged him with DWI and drug possession. They also seized the vehicle. 

When Barkley went down to police headquarters, he was informed that they intended to keep the vehicle permanently under forfeiture laws. Barkley, who's an attorney, was appalled. http://strib.mn/1n4r50K

It's *finally* beginning to look like summer.

status_message:
Preserving the prairie, using nature's way

It's prairie burn season, as controlled fires begin around the state in order to manage and rejuvenate prairie habitats. Here, fire crews checked the line earlier this week during a burn at Cedar Creek Natural History Area near Bethel, in the northern metro area. The area is part of the University of Minnesota's Cedar Creek Ecosystem Science Reserve research site, which contains elements of the three major ecosystems of the continent. Photo: Brian Person, Star Tribune

Share your memories: Thanksgiving is still a few days away, but it's time to start thinking about the next holidays. So unpack your seasonal decor, relive your holiday memories and share them. Whatever you celebrate — Christmas, Hanukkah or Kwanzaa — we want to know how you make the season bright. 

Do you have a favorite decoration or heirloom that you display year after year? Or is there a holiday decorating ritual that has special meaning to you?

Your heirloom doesn't have to be fancy or expensive. It can be odd or even ugly. We're looking for things with a story behind them. Send a brief description and a digital photo to kim.palmer@startribune.com. The deadline is Dec. 10.

A shopper chooses an apple Wednesday during the grand opening of the Whole Foods store in the North Loop neighborhood of Minneapolis. The store isn't the city's first urban grocery store -- downtown is book-ended by two Lund's stores at nearly opposite ends of Hennepin Avenue -- but the arrival of the store represents a significant moment in the transformation of the once-sleepy North Loop neighborhood, which has become one of the city's fastest-growing neighborhoods. Share your back-to-school story: Remember the time your parents put you on a bus to the wrong school? Or the time an upperclassman gave you directions to your classroom on the nonexistent third floor? Going back to school is always an adventure, no matter what decade you went. What is your most memorable back-to-school adventure? Share your anecdotes, and we'll publish the best ones in an upcoming Variety edition. 

Send entries to: Back to School Stories, Star Tribune, Variety section, 425 Portland Av. S., Minneapolis, MN 55488. Or e-mail your stories to tellus@startribune.com. We'd need the stories by Sunday, Aug. 25. Thanks!

status_message:
Do you remember playing Twister?

Charles Foley, the #Minnesota man whose #Twister game launched decades of awkward social interactions at parties has died. 

Twister debuted in 1966 with the slogan,"The Game That Ties You Up in Knots." While Twister was the highest profile of his 97 patented inventions, Foley's Un-Du became the product of choice for photographers, scrapbookers, and even law enforcement officials and the staff at the Library of Congress, who use the adhesive remover that takes off stickers, tape and labels without leaving a stain.

Read the story: http://strib.mn/189vA1G

status_message:
Here's the latest on the storm's aftermath and the upcoming forecast:

• Hennepin County says some sirens might be without power after Friday's storm and asks residents to monitor multiple sources for weather updates.

• As of 3 p.m., about 173,000 Xcel Energy customers were without power in the Twin Cities and elsewhere in Minnesota, with the utility having crews spread out and working on restoring service.

• In downtown Robbinsdale, a gaping sinkhole at least 30 feet across drew "gawkers, lots of them," along with police and fire department vehicles to block off the area.

• The Twin Cities office of the National Weather Service indicated that during the weekend, 3 inches or more of additional rain could be expected over the metro area and elsewhere in the region.

You had to want it to go fishing today: Cold and wind -- and ice -- spiced an opener already wounded by lingering wintry weather.

Minnesota anglers were greeted by temperatures far colder than just one day before, by a cold and gusty north wind and by ice still covering the largest Up North lakes. Bactrian camels are native to the steppes of central Asia. They have two humps on their backs, in contrast to the more common, single-humped dromedary camel -- although this little guy's humps aren't well defined yet.

Gov. Dayton's budget overhaul has taken blistering criticism from lawyers, public relations firms, accountants and IT firms that would have to charge sales tax on their fees if the budget is approved. But the plan would lower state sales tax from 6.875 percent to 5.5 percent on some services and help remedy a patchwork system that favors some businesses over others, often for no apparent reason.

For example, Minnesota sales tax applies to pet grooming but not barber shops, dry cleaners but not coin-operated laundromats, and calls to 1-900 numbers but not dating services. Super Bowl tickets are exempt, but not hockey sticks.

status_message:
Have you seen this before?

Minnehaha Falls was little more than a drip Thursday. Step into the creek these days and you won't even get your feet wet. With little rain, flow dwindled in late summer, and the dam that lets water from Lake Minnetonka into the creek was closed Aug. 20.

The only source of water for the creek has been rain water that runs off streets or through the ground, and since Aug. 1, Twin Cities rainfall has been about one-fourth normal. The phenomenon is not uncommon. The dam was closed for most of the summer in 2009, and for the entire summer of 2000, when the creek also reverted to a gravel bed.  

Photo: Jeff Wheeler, Star Tribune

Do you remember the moon landing?

Armstrong commanded the Apollo 11 spacecraft that landed on the moon July 20, 1969, capping the most daring of the 20th century's scientific expeditions. His first words after setting foot on the surface are etched in history books and the memories of those who heard them in a live broadcast.

"That's one small step for (a) man, one giant leap for mankind," Armstrong said.

Amid drumming, chanting and the smell of sacred burning sage, about 300 people gathered Friday on the border between South Dakota and Minnesota to symbolically welcome home Dakota people exiled from the state following the U.S. Dakota-War which began 150 years ago. 

The ceremony was rich with symbolism as eight Dakota  grandmothers – four on each side of the border – exchanged eagle feathers and sage to remember all the lost lives and spirits since the bitter war. Story: http://strib.mn/N68kv2
